Soviet peasant filled with burning desire to read for glory of Soviet Russia. One day peasant go to Soviet bookstore, and sees book with skull on cover.
He asks owner how much is book, and owner responds 80 rubles. However, owner tell peasant never read last page, or else doom shall fall upon him!
Peasant reads all book in one night, is dark book of capitalism about by evil man, John Deere, talking of automated machinery and air conditioned tractors, many horrors in book indeed!
Yet peasant does not read last page, for he has fear in his heart! One night it storms however, and the man is bored. He finally gathers up enough Soviet courage to read last page, dispelling superstition, for he has faith in the Party.
As soon as he reads last page, man gasps! Book originally 20 rubles! The owner was Jew!

What's the rationale for the "If the charset attribute is specified, the element must be the first element in the head element of the file." requirement in the current spec? So what do current parsers do for instances where the meta@charset or meta@http-equiv=Content-Type is not the first element in the head? OK I think that the requirement to have it be the first element in the head is not going to be intuitive to users so conformance checkers should ideally have an explicit message making it clear that it needs to be. b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9 - validator.nu currently doesn't seem to produce a useful error message for the case if it's not the first element in the head with charset='' b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9 - for validator.nu/?out=text output for valid documents, I wonder whether it shouldn't better emit nothing at all rather than "The document is valid HTML5..." ah yeah, it is I wonder what other apps do now when they need to include URIs in gnu-style error messages and still want they to be parse-able heh b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9 - I think Xalan is significantly slower than Saxon b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9 - yeah, I think that would be good b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9 - but are you talking about Saxon 6 or later Saxon (8 or 9)? Saxon 6 is in right in libs in Debian not in non-free OK dunno. There's even a GCJ version of Saxon packaged for Debian yeah, me neither b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9 - source for HTML5 spec is still only around 2MB?

Because if you change charset, it can change the meaning of a previous element Unless the charset claims to be utf-16 (but that's unrelated) Might be, I don't have perfect information available gnum - gnu umproved At least one will say the spec has been published, in a way that suggests it's complete

a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: to make the parser restart as early as possible a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: they restart later a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: must be first is a doc conformance req a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: so docs that don't conform still work but give worse browser performance a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: don't they still restart but as UTF-8? a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: yeah a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: did you try with charset='' or the HTML4 syntax? a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: ok a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: out=text is supposed to be human-readable a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: for emacs parsing, I want to have out=gnu but the gnu spec is bad I suppose I could just bite the bullet and hard-code "-" as the file name to sidestep the issue of putting URIs in the gnu format and to use the v.nu style of column counting instead of what gnu specifies most of the time people wouldn't notice... but then there are always those edge cases... we need GNU error format 5 hmm. validating the html5 spec even locally is very, very slow I wonder if my show source impl is bad or whether I've changed something in the schematron schema that makes the xslt impl go crazy or if it is just that Xalan is much much slower than Saxon a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: I suppose going back to Saxon for non-Debian installations would make sense then if Saxon were modified to support column numbers in addition to line numbers a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: 6. using 8 would also involve getting rid of the XSLT 1.0 warning a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: hmm. that seems like a violation of Debian's own policy... a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: interesting given the whole Debian vs. pre-tri-license Mozilla thing a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: and the debial-legal stance of CDDL I'd guess Saxon just flew under the debia-legal radar, but I don't know. hmm. typoed debian twice... the perf problem definitely is the Schematron part--not show source... a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: yes

Is there some specific distinction between "support" and "advocate" that I am missing ? "I expect poll survey from Apple representatives would support an MIT license" vs "we have yet to have somebody specifically advocate for [the MIT license]" The question is whether merely having supporters rather than advocates should be sufficient to exclude an option from the poll That seems like an insane policy in a consensus driven environment (which maybe licensing discussions aren't but still) It is quite easy to imagine that there are people who can live with the MIT that cannot live with CC0 but prefer an Option X license and people who cannot live with an Option X license, can live with MIT, but prefer CC0 It seems Apple may be an example of the former and Mozilla of the latter Note: *may* Obviously I don't actually know what these organisations will say

hi!  How do you guys feel about Apple's <input type="search">? I see tons of sites using JS/CSS hacks to implement similar functionality; it seems like standardizing it should be helpful, and Apple already has a working implementation. here's the details as I understand them:  https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=456229 I've heard that the "placeholder" option is being added to all (relevant) input types (not just search); I'm not sure if that's an official HTML 5 thing or just something Mozilla is doing. agreed that makes sense. the main issue is, right now everybody is reinventing the wheel, and some implementations are better than others. if there were a standard way to do it in HTML, that everybody could use, then they'd just use that, and either use JS to fake compatibility with old browsers (same as they're doing now), or let old browsers have reduced functionality if that's easier. 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c: that Mozilla bug was something I recently submitted, when I couldn't find an existing one. I attempted to describe Apple's implementation, but that doesn't mean Mozilla is actually doing it. I think they did say placeholder will be supported soon though. well, one of the things Google mentioned was that they feel Safari's rounded corners would be inappropriate on Windows, so they'd like to come up with a different appearance oh, I gotcha no, I think web designers aren't too picky about the appearance, although obviously I'd expect Apple to continue making the search box on www.apple.com look the way it does today personally I love the little magnifying glass icon - it's a bit weird that it's the "results" option that makes it appear, but having a tiny little icon like that, that I don't have to make myself, the appearance of which could be platform-specific, would be great. heh, well yeah, that's what I meant ;-) yeah, Firefox uses it for things like the download window I recently implemented something where I wanted the functionality to basically work like searching in iTunes - it filters the results with each keypress.  I had to experiment with using onkeypress, onkeydown, onkeyup, see what worked and what didn't I wound up using setTimeout with a 50ms delay, to make sure the value of the textbox would have changed by the time my function was called... and added code to that function to copy the value to a variable, after checking to see if it was different, to avoid repeatedly searching for the same string anyway, it just felt like I was reinventing the wheel, and probably poorly. also, in my case, I want the little magnifying glass icon to indicate the purpose of the box, because I don't want to take the space to add a label, and using a placeholder isn't appropriate because I automatically focus on page load (so the user can immediately start typing to filter search results).
a while back lachlan & mpt also (briefly) made the case for <input type="search"> here: http://lists.whatwg.org/htdig.cgi/whatwg-whatwg.org/2007-May/011367.html

likes <input type="search"> and also placeholder which is separately useful even for non-search input types WebKit has placeholder on all text-like input types some of the <input type="search> stuff duplicates more general mechanisms in WF2 I would like to deprecate them when we add the relevant WF2 stuff but not sure we can ever remove well incremental and the event that results would be oninput in WF2 Mozilla sounds like they are just copying what WebKit has so I don't think there is reinvention exactly 3e49d4426c0b776106a241ca6729ba2a: I see I think it would probably be better to support <input type="search"> with the relevant WF2 replacement features
we already have code to style search boxes with platform-specific look we use it in XUL

e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0: I could have told you not to bother responding to him a long time ago.  He like to use the equivalent of the "Pokemon test" in his arguments a lot. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:POKEMON basically, arguing that if X is good enough, then Y is also.  (He did the same for other features. e.g. listing code, kbd, samp and var and arguing that if they're included, so should whatever he wants) you could try responding with the chewbacca defence, it'd be as effective as anything else ;-) e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0: here's an abstract for you to add to that draft: This document describes the set of guiding principles used by the HTML Working Group for the development of HTML5.  The principles are designed to offer guidance for the design of HTML, in the areas of compatibility, utility and interoperability. we're going to need to resolve those disputed principles before it's finished, though I support publishing it as a WD yeah, will do

MikeSmith, I agree about the utility of an organized decision rationale. The wiki seems to be the mechanism of choice so far. Have you used it much? also... I'm curious as to how comments on mobileOK Basic Tests 1.0 are tracked. any pointers? ok, I think I'm gonna put the question on html4-differences v1.25 is mjs around? I wonder what response options to offer. maybe yes, abstain, no, formally object none well, it contributes to the evidence that the WG is making an informed decision. maybe just a little. "working draft headed for note" seems best for status ok, take a look: http://www.w3.org/2002/09/wbs/40318/trdiff/ the one objection I can see is "we should do design principles instead". I'm OK to do design principles *also*... I wonder if it's worth some discussion first, though changes the start date to tomorrow to avoid dirty data just while I'm mulling it over e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0, are you interested/willing to work with mjs to format the design principles as a /TR/? (sandro has some tools to make a /TR/ out of wiki topics automatically; I wonder if it's worth a try) http://esw.w3.org/topic/HTML/ProposedDesignPrinciples is a draft of sorts would like to chat with dbaron and mjs for just a bit checking the history of the wiki topic... good: no anonymous edits. all those names should go in the acks section I could (a) put the question on diffs now or (b) try to get design principles in similar shape real quick and put the questions on both of them simultaneously. any strong opinions? e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0? how close is chaals? you guys aren't in the same building or anything, are you? once you make a copy of the wiki topic in the dev.w3.org CVS repostitory, does that become the "truth", or can we continue to welcome edits to the wiki topic and port them over? yeah; poor choice of words... is in the habit of using "truth" when talking about multiple version-control repositories and sync issues hmm... "France Telecom has joined the HTML Working Group" I don't see as much reference to the design principles as I'd like. I seem to recall argument that echoes some of the principles without referring to them by name/URI e.g. Hixie writes "Several features have been designed and then removed from HTML5 after flaws in the fallback behaviour were pointed out. We have in fact been ruthless about ensuring this." that seems pretty close to the "Degrade Gracefully" principle, but doesn't invoke it by name the short version of "Degrade Gracefully" is hard for me to grok: "New versions of HTML should allow documents using them to work in user agents that don't yet support it." noodles... "HTML documents that include markup for new features should work reasonably well in old [extant?] user agents" by port you mean to CVS, right? that changes the social arrangement from "it's a wiki -- fix it yourself" to "mail suggested changes and an editor will consider them" I sorta think I should get mjs in the loop for making such a change. well, I understood "lets first port the thing to HTML before making improvements :)" as push-back against continued tweaking of the wiki topic I started making a survey with separate questions for each design principle, but it didn't go easily. oops; "Visible Metadata" is among the design principles there. it's disputed, but it's there. I didn't realize that when I suggested closing the 'fear of "invisible metadata"' thread. HTML/ProposedDesignPrinciples in its present state doesn't really appeal to me. I have a hard time proposing it to the WG when I don't really like it that much. hmm mail mjs and copy public-html , a la "what do you think?" that's perhaps a lot to ask... anything from "yeah, please run with that; I'm snowed under but somebody should keep it moving" to "hang on a bit; I'm snowed under just now, but I'm not sure we should move from the wiki just now" others might chime in a la "I don't agree with #4; it should be moved to the disputed section or changed _thusly_ or deleted" or mjs might say "great; ok, I committed a few changes too. feel free to mail more change requests and I'll consider them" er... I thought you did already I'm totally on the fence; I'm as much following your lead as advising you. ok, I just put the question on html4-differences thanks for moving the ball forward on design principles; I wanted some visible progress on that before putting this question. yeah, that looks like a WBS bug, e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0. whats the difference of NAT on the OUTPUT chain   and after that on the POSTROUTING  chain ? whats the dif? Apachez, would the postrouting be used if the box was acring as a router ? acting*

depends on your needs if you nat on output then only traffic originating from the box itself will be nated but if you nat on postrouting then basically all traffic will be nated (that is traffic that matches your nat rule like "-s 192.168.0.0/24 -d externalip" or similar) best practise would be to use the nating in postrouting no matter what that is because postrouting chain is part of the nat table -t nat -A POSTROUTING that is why for example you need two rules in order to perform a port forward through the wall first a  -t nat -A PREROUTING rule which will alter the packet to internal adress and port it should be sent to and then a -a FORWARD rule which allows the packet to pass the wall
yes, only the postrouting. output would only be used for locally generated traffic, not for traffic passing over the box.

MIME type of application/xhtml+xml or application/xml ? 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: ah, that clears my confusion so HTML5 text/html is fine with MathML, SVG and HTML perfect!  Thank you. 1f8387eb43f131d7c309a90a4e36b5cb: ok i will be and i plan on being here in the channel frequently as i work, to give back for others who have questions and to ask some of my own i'm sure.

91cfbb9d0d2d873280a77dc8a3d50644: it's a DOM vocabulary, and there's an XML serialisation and a text/html serialisation text/html (as of HTML5) supports the MathML, SVG, and HTML vocabularies for XML, you can use any MIME type text/xml, application/xml, or */*+xml as far as HTML5 goes ok, so, elementary TCP questions ahoy. if i want to initiate a graceful close, it seems relatively easy I send a FIN (shutdown with SHUT_WR), then I wait until the socket is ready to read and recv() returns zero, then I call close(). but what does the other side do? If I'm in full swing of a connection, and my peer sends a FIN (recv() returns zero), what do I do to make sure that all my sent data gets to the other side? I can't call close(), because that will empty the send buffer and send a RST, as far as I can tell. I can't call shutdown() with SHUT_WR, because I'll have no way to know to move on to the next step, since recv() has already returned zero. hm, it seems i'm wrong about close() clearing the _send_ buffer what's going on is normally it sends an RST if there's any pending data to _read_, and _that_ causes the other side to throw away _its_ read buffer so a simple graceful shutdown can be done just by one side or the other sending a FIN then it waiting for recv()=0 and calling close() and the other side just calling close() when it gets recv()=0
91cfbb9d0d2d873280a77dc8a3d50644: Just be careful when using namespaced elements.  IIRC they sometimes don't act as you'd expect in the text/html serialization.

W3C Definition of Concensus: "Consensus: A substantial number of individuals in the set support the decision and nobody in the set registers a Formal Objection. Individuals in the set may abstain. Abstention is either an explicit expression of no opinion or silence by an individual in the set.
